data.enText: to exist or be very common at a particular time or in a particular place

data.chText: 地方监狱的普遍状况让我们震惊。
data.enText: We were horrified at the conditions prevailing in local prisons.

data.chText: 这些信念在某些社会群体中仍很盛行。
data.enText: Those beliefs still prevail among certain social groups.
to be accepted, especially after a struggle or an argument

data.chText: （尤指长时间斗争后）战胜，挫败
data.enText: to defeat an opponent, especially after a long struggle
prevail on/upon sb to do sth
to persuade sb to do sth

data.chText: 我相信能说服他来做一次报告。
data.enText: I'm sure he could be prevailed upon to give a talk.

simple_means.memory_skill: pre 前 + vail 强壮的 → 在前面很强大 → 获胜；流行

means: (尤指长时间斗争后)战胜，挫败

ex.chText: 他们肯定能打赢这场篮球赛。
ex.enText: They are sure to win this basketball match.

ex.chText: 那项发明为他赢得了一枚奖章。
ex.enText: That invention won him a medal.

ex.chText: 去年我们又获得了大丰收。
ex.enText: Last year we won another rich harvest.

synonyms.bx: 指在比赛、竞赛、选举、战争等中击败对手，成为胜利者。

ex.chText: 西班牙人于16世纪征服了新大陆。
ex.enText: The Spanish conquered the New World in the sixteenth century.

ex.chText: 科学家什么时候能征服恒星呢?
ex.enText: When will scientists conquer the stars?

ex.chText: 人类正在学会征服各种自然灾害。
ex.enText: Human beings are learning to conquer all kinds of natural disasters.

synonyms.bx: 含义广泛，既可指凭借武力或精神、道德方面的力量使对方屈服，又可指在排除阻力、障碍后取得胜利，强调不仅击败对方，而且还使对方臣服。

ex.chText: 政府军最终制服了反叛武装。
ex.enText: Government troops have finally overcome the rebel forces.

ex.chText: 第二语言学习者有许多障碍要克服
ex.enText: The learner of a second language has many obstacles to overcom

ex.chText: 她努力克服自己的羞怯。
ex.enText: She struggled to overcome her shyness.

synonyms.bx: 既可指在战斗、竞赛等中战胜对手，又可指在工作、学习等方面克服困难，也可指控制感情，克服某种不良心理。

ex.chText: 在这个问题上，谁也不能使对方折服。
ex.enText: It was an argument in which neither side could prevail over the other.

ex.chText: 主队最终以86比75击败了意大利队。
ex.enText: The host team eventually prevailed over the Italian team 86-75.

synonyms.bx: 指某人、某种观点或原则通过斗争、争辩等而获胜，常后接介词 over。

data.enText: prevail on/upon sb to do sth
to persuade sb to do sth

data.chText: 我相信能说服他来做一次报告。
data.enText: I'm sure he could be prevailed upon to give a talk.

example: He prevailed upon her to visit his parents
The champion prevailed, though it was a hard fight

tr: be larger in number, quantity, power, status or importance

value.def: If a proposal, principle, or opinion prevails, it gains influence or is accepted, often after a struggle or argument.

example.ex: We hope that common sense would prevail...
example.tran: 我们希望情理会占上风。

example.ex: Rick still believes that justice will prevail...
example.tran: 里克仍然相信正义会得以伸张。

example.ex: Political and personal ambitions are starting to prevail over economic interests.
example.tran: 政治抱负和个人野心开始压倒经济利益。

value.tran: （提议、原则、观点）占上风，占优势，获胜，被接受

value.def: If a situation, attitude, or custom prevails in a particular place at a particular time, it is normal or most common in that place at that time.

example.ex: A similar situation prevails in America...
example.tran: 相似的情况在美国随处可见。

example.ex: ...the confusion which had prevailed at the time of the revolution...
example.tran: 在革命期间普遍存在的混乱

example.ex: How people in a certain era bury their dead says much about the prevailing attitudes toward death.
example.tran: 某个特定时代的人们如何埋葬逝者很大程度上反映出当时人们对待死亡的普遍态度。

value.tran: （情形、态度、风俗）盛行，流行，普遍

value.def: If one side in a battle, contest, or dispute prevails, it wins.

example.ex: He appears to have the votes he needs to prevail...
example.tran: 他似乎已经获得了取胜所需的选票。

example.ex: I do hope he will prevail over the rebels.
example.tran: 我确实希望他能战胜叛乱者。

value.tran: （在战斗、竞赛、争论中）获胜，取胜

value.def: If you prevail upon someone to do something, you succeed in persuading them to do it.

example.ex: We must, each of us, prevail upon our congressman to act...
example.tran: 我们每一个人都必须说服我们各自的国会议员采取行动。

example.ex: Do you think she could be prevailed upon to do those things?
example.tran: 你觉得有可能说服她去做那些事情吗？

trans: 劝说(说服)...；说服；劝说；诱使
